Mean Squared Error (MSE)
Now that we’ve seen MAE, let’s move to another common evaluation metric: Mean Squared Error (MSE).
MSE measures how far predictions are from actual values.
Instead of just taking absolute errors, it squares the errors first and then takes the average.

MSE = 1/n * ∑ n i=1 (Yi - Yi^)^2

Why Square the Errors?

No Negative Canceling → Squaring ensures errors don’t cancel out.
Penalizes Large Mistakes → Bigger errors grow much more after squaring.
Example:

Error = 2 → 2^2 = 4
Error = 5 → 5^2 = 25 (much bigger impact!)

Intuition

MAE → “On average, how much am I off?”
MSE → “On average, how big are my squared mistakes?”
If you want to heavily punish large mistakes, MSE is better.
Example (Conceptual)

Suppose we predict exam scores:

Student	Actual (y)	Predicted (ŷ)	Error (y-ŷ)	Squared Error
A	50	48	-2	4
B	60	65	-5	25
C	70	68	+2	4
D	80	75	-5	25

MSE = (4+25+4+25)/4 = 14.5 
The Mean Squared Error = 14.5

The number itself doesn’t use the same units (it’s in squared units).
If scores are in marks → MSE is in marks².
That’s why sometimes people prefer RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error) to bring it back to the same unit.

